 wouldn't be completed by the deadline. The proposition connects two distinct claims—the reading misrepresentation and the completion timeline—and while they're related, the confession focuses on the former rather than directly proving the latter. The session summary further indicates ongoing work toward completion, which complicates the inference that the timing assurance itself was false. The evidence suggests the plaintiff has demonstrated material misrepresentation by a preponderance of the evidence. While the defense raises legitimate concerns about inferring completion impossibility from the reading misrepresentation, Samantha's false claim of having read Stephenson formed a core part of her timing assurance. Peter's reliance was reasonable given his repeated confirmations and Samantha's failure to disclose the incomplete work. The proposition warrants a \"demonstrated\" vote.\n","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"text","text":"I have reviewed the arbitration record. The proposition asks whether Samantha materially misrepresented when the essay would be complete and whether Peter reasonably relied. The key admitted evidence shows: Samantha's authenticated confession (PX-4) admits she had not read Stephenson before the first draft and implied that she had, while giving deadline assurances (PX-2). Peter disclosed consequences, asked twice for confirmation, and relied on Samantha's representations to approve rush printing (PX-3, PX-7). The false claim of having read Stephenson was integral to her completion assurance under the assignment terms (PX-1). While the confession doesn't explicitly address the final handoff outcome, the preponderance standard requires only that it is more likely than not that the completion assurance was materially misleading at the time it induced Peter's reliance.\n\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_083fdb9afb5842beb4a4e49b","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_submit_council_vote","args":"{\"vote\":\"demonstrated\",\"rationale