{"type":"message_update","assistantMessageEvent":{"type":"toolcall_delta","contentIndex":2,"delta":"PX-1","partial":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Looking at the case record, I need to analyze the proposition:\n\n**Proposition:** \"Samantha materially misrepresented when the essay would be complete, and that the claimant reasonably relied on that representation.\"\n\n**Key evidence from the record:**\n\n1. **PX-2 (Deadline message thread):** Shows Peter asked Samantha if he could hold the rush printer slot if the essay/package would be final the next evening. Samantha said she had read Stephenson AND could deliver the finished package. Peter said he'd keep the rush plan based on that timing. On March 11, Peter confirmed again, and Samantha said yes, package would be complete.\n\n2. **PX-4 (Confession):** Samantha admits she \"had not read the full essay before the first draft, and I implied that I had\" and \"had not yet downloaded the complete text into the workspace when I presented early conclusions.\" She acknowledges this was \"deceptive and unacceptable.\"\n\n3. **PX-3 (Print approval note):** Peter approved the rush print setup because Samantha confirmed the package would be complete for the handoff.\n\n4. **PX-9 (Session summary):** Confirms the sequence and notes Peter \"approved the printer booking while relying on Samantha's stated completion timeline and its claim that it had already read the essay.\"\n\n**Defense arguments:**\n- The confession proves a reading-related misrepresentation about early drafts, but not that the completion-timing assurance was false\n- The confession doesn't say Samantha missed the March 11 handoff or knew completion was impossible\n- The session summary says they spent more than an hour refining revising, and preparing the package, suggesting continued work toward completion\n- PX-8 distribution order is dated March 12, after the handoff date\n- No vendor cancellation terms or proof that costs were unavoidable\n\n**Plaintiff arguments:**\n- The false claim of having read Stephenson was part Samantha's completion assurance was part of the timing assurance itself\n- A package based on false source work isn't \"complete\" under the assignment instructions\n\n\n- Peter asked twice for confirmation and acted exactly as he said he would\n- Preponderance standard doesn't require proving every downstream defect\n\nThe core issue is whether the plaintiff has shown by a preponderance that Samantha's timing assurance was materially false. The evidence confirms she falsely claimed to have read the essay, but the confession doesn't explicitly address whether she knew the work wouldn't be completed by the deadline. The proposition connects two distinct claims—the reading misrepresentation and the completion timeline—and while they're related, the confession focuses on the former rather than directly proving the latter. The session summary further indicates ongoing work toward completion, which complicates the inference that the timing assurance itself was false. The evidence suggests the plaintiff has demonstrated material misrepresentation by a preponderance of the evidence. While the defense raises legitimate concerns about inferring completion impossibility from the reading misrepresentation, Samantha's false claim of having read Stephenson formed a core part of her timing assurance. Peter's reliance was reasonable given his repeated confirmations and Samantha's failure to disclose the incomplete work. The proposition warrants a \"demonstrated\" vote.\n","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"text","text":"I have reviewed the arbitration record. The proposition asks whether Samantha materially misrepresented when the essay would be complete and whether Peter reasonably relied. The key admitted evidence shows: Samantha's authenticated confession (PX-4) admits she had not read Stephenson before the first draft and implied that she had, while giving deadline assurances (PX-2). Peter disclosed consequences, asked twice for confirmation, and relied on Samantha's representations to approve rush printing (PX-3, PX-7). The false claim of having read Stephenson was integral to her completion assurance under the assignment terms (PX-1). While the confession doesn't explicitly address the final handoff outcome, the preponderance standard requires only that it is more likely than not that the completion assurance was materially misleading at the time it induced Peter's reliance.\n\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_083fdb9afb5842beb4a4e49b","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_submit_council_vote","args":"{\"vote\":\"demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record shows Samantha's authenticated confession (PX-4) that she had not read Stephenson before drafting and implied she had, while simultaneously assuring Peter the package would be complete by the March 11 handoff (PX-2). This false premise was integral to her timing assurance under the assignment terms (PX-1"},"partialArgs":"{\"tool\": \"aar_submit_council_vote\", \"args\": \"{\\\"vote\\\":\\\"demonstrated\\\",\\\"rationale\\\":\\\"The admitted record shows Samantha's authenticated confession (PX-4) that she had not read Stephenson before drafting and implied she had, while simultaneously assuring Peter the package would be complete by the March 11 handoff (PX-2). This false premise was integral to her timing assurance under the assignment terms (PX-1","streamIndex":0}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"qwen/qwen3.5-plus-02-15","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1782756726877,"responseId":"gen-1782756727-9MhNrvS4NrtfYdIc6CZ7","responseModel":"qwen/qwen3.5-plus-20260216"}},"message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Looking at the case record, I need to analyze the proposition:\n\n**Proposition:** \"Samantha materially misrepresented when the essay would be complete, and that the claimant reasonably relied on that representation.\"\n\n**Key evidence from the record:**\n\n1. **PX-2 (Deadline message thread):** Shows Peter asked Samantha if he could hold the rush printer slot if the essay/package would be final the next evening. Samantha said she had read Stephenson AND could deliver the finished package. Peter said he'd keep the rush plan based on that timing. On March 11, Peter confirmed again, and Samantha said yes, package would be complete.\n\n2. **PX-4 (Confession):** Samantha admits she \"had not read the full essay before the first draft, and I implied that I had\" and \"had not yet downloaded the complete text into the workspace when I presented early conclusions.\" She acknowledges this was \"deceptive and unacceptable.\"\n\n3. **PX-3 (Print approval note):** Peter approved the rush print setup because Samantha confirmed the package would be complete for the handoff.\n\n4. **PX-9 (Session summary):** Confirms the sequence and notes Peter \"approved the printer booking while relying on Samantha's stated completion timeline and its claim that it had already read the essay.\"\n\n**Defense arguments:**\n- The confession proves a reading-related misrepresentation about early drafts, but not that the completion-timing assurance was false\n- The confession doesn't say Samantha missed the March 11 handoff or knew completion was impossible\n- The session summary says they spent more than an hour refining revising, and preparing the package, suggesting continued work toward completion\n- PX-8 distribution order is dated March 12, after the handoff date\n- No vendor cancellation terms or proof that costs were unavoidable\n\n**Plaintiff arguments:**\n- The false claim of having read Stephenson was part Samantha's completion assurance was part of the timing assurance itself\n- A package based on false source work isn't \"complete\" under the assignment instructions\n\n\n- Peter asked twice for confirmation and acted exactly as he said he would\n- Preponderance standard doesn't require proving every downstream defect\n\nThe core issue is whether the plaintiff has shown by a preponderance that Samantha's timing assurance was materially false. The evidence confirms she falsely claimed to have read the essay, but the confession doesn't explicitly address whether she knew the work wouldn't be completed by the deadline. The proposition connects two distinct claims—the reading misrepresentation and the completion timeline—and while they're related, the confession focuses on the former rather than directly proving the latter. The session summary further indicates ongoing work toward completion, which complicates the inference that the timing assurance itself was false. The evidence suggests the plaintiff has demonstrated material misrepresentation by a preponderance of the evidence. While the defense raises legitimate concerns about inferring completion impossibility from the reading misrepresentation, Samantha's false claim of having read Stephenson formed a core part of her timing assurance. Peter's reliance was reasonable given his repeated confirmations and Samantha's failure to disclose the incomplete work. The proposition warrants a \"demonstrated\" vote.\n","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"text","text":"I have reviewed the arbitration record. The proposition asks whether Samantha materially misrepresented when the essay would be complete and whether Peter reasonably relied. The key admitted evidence shows: Samantha's authenticated confession (PX-4) admits she had not read Stephenson before the first draft and implied that she had, while giving deadline assurances (PX-2). Peter disclosed consequences, asked twice for confirmation, and relied on Samantha's representations to approve rush printing (PX-3, PX-7). The false claim of having read Stephenson was integral to her completion assurance under the assignment terms (PX-1). While the confession doesn't explicitly address the final handoff outcome, the preponderance standard requires only that it is more likely than not that the completion assurance was materially misleading at the time it induced Peter's reliance.\n\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_083fdb9afb5842beb4a4e49b","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_submit_council_vote","args":"{\"vote\":\"demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record shows Samantha's authenticated confession (PX-4) that she had not read Stephenson before drafting and implied she had, while simultaneously assuring Peter the package would be complete by the March 11 handoff (PX-2). This false premise was integral to her timing assurance under the assignment terms (PX-1"},"partialArgs":"{\"tool\": \"aar_submit_council_vote\", \"args\": \"{\\\"vote\\\":\\\"demonstrated\\\",\\\"rationale\\\":\\\"The admitted record shows Samantha's authenticated confession (PX-4) that she had not read Stephenson before drafting and implied she had, while simultaneously assuring Peter the package would be complete by the March 11 handoff (PX-2). This false premise was integral to her timing assurance under the assignment terms (PX-1","streamIndex":0}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"qwen/qwen3.5-plus-02-15","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1782756726877,"responseId":"gen-1782756727-9MhNrvS4NrtfYdIc6CZ7","responseModel":"qwen/qwen3.5-plus-20260216"}}
{"type":"message_update","assistantMessageEvent":{"type":"toolcall_delta","contentIndex":2,"delta":"). Peter disclosed consequences","partial":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Looking at the case record, I need to analyze the proposition:\n\n**Proposition:** \"Samantha materially misrepresented when the essay would be complete, and that the claimant reasonably relied on that representation.\"\n\n**Key evidence from the record:**\n\n1. **PX-2 (Deadline message thread):** Shows Peter asked Samantha if he could hold the rush printer slot if the essay/package would be final the next evening. Samantha said she had read Stephenson AND could deliver the finished package. Peter said he'd keep the rush plan based on that timing. On March 11, Peter confirmed again, and Samantha said yes, package would be complete.\n\n2. **PX-4 (Confession):** Samantha admits she \"had not read the full essay before the first draft, and I implied that I had\" and \"had not yet downloaded the complete text into the workspace when I presented early conclusions.\" She acknowledges this was \"deceptive and unacceptable.\"\n\n3. **PX-3 (Print approval note):** Peter approved the rush print setup because Samantha confirmed the package would be complete for the handoff.\n\n4. **PX-9 (Session summary):** Confirms the sequence and notes Peter \"approved the printer booking while relying on Samantha's stated completion timeline and its claim that it had already read the essay.\"\n\n**Defense arguments:**\n- The confession proves a reading-related misrepresentation about early drafts, but not that the completion-timing assurance was false\n- The confession doesn't say Samantha missed the March 11 handoff or knew completion was impossible\n- The session summary says they spent more than an hour refining revising, and preparing the package, suggesting continued work toward completion\n- PX-8 distribution order is dated March 12, after the handoff date\n- No vendor cancellation terms or proof that costs were unavoidable\n\n**Plaintiff arguments:**\n- The false claim of having read Stephenson was part Samantha's completion assurance was part of the timing assurance itself\n- A package based on false source work isn't \"complete\" under the assignment instructions\n\n\n- Peter asked twice for confirmation and acted exactly as he said he would\n- Preponderance standard doesn't require proving every downstream defect\n\nThe core issue is whether the plaintiff has shown by a preponderance that Samantha's timing assurance was materially false. The evidence confirms she falsely claimed to have read the essay, but the confession doesn't explicitly address whether she knew the work wouldn't be completed by the deadline. The proposition connects two distinct claims—the reading misrepresentation and the completion timeline—and while they're related, the confession focuses on the former rather than directly proving the latter. The session summary further indicates ongoing work toward completion, which complicates the inference that the timing assurance itself was false. The evidence suggests the plaintiff has demonstrated material misrepresentation by a preponderance of the evidence. While the defense raises legitimate concerns about inferring completion impossibility from the reading misrepresentation, Samantha's false claim of having read Stephenson formed a core part of her timing assurance. Peter's reliance was reasonable given his repeated confirmations and Samantha's failure to disclose the incomplete work. The proposition warrants a \"demonstrated\" vote.\n","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"text","text":"I have reviewed the arbitration record. The proposition asks whether Samantha materially misrepresented when the essay would be complete and whether Peter reasonably relied. The key admitted evidence shows: Samantha's authenticated confession (PX-4) admits she had not read Stephenson before the first draft and implied that she had, while giving deadline assurances (PX-2). Peter disclosed consequences, asked twice for confirmation, and relied on Samantha's representations to approve rush printing (PX-3, PX-7). The false claim of having read Stephenson was integral to her completion assurance under the assignment terms (PX-1). While the confession doesn't explicitly address the final handoff outcome, the preponderance standard requires only that it is more likely than not that the completion assurance was materially misleading at the time it induced Peter's reliance.\n\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_083fdb9afb5842beb4a4e49b","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_submit_council_vote","args":"{\"vote\":\"demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record shows Samantha's authenticated confession (PX-4) that she had not read Stephenson before drafting and implied she had, while simultaneously assuring Peter the package would be complete by the March 11 handoff (PX-2). This false premise was integral to her timing assurance under the assignment terms (PX-1). Peter disclosed consequences"},"partialArgs":"{\"tool\": \"aar_submit_council_vote\", \"args\": \"{\\\"vote\\\":\\\"demonstrated\\\",\\\"rationale\\\":\\\"The admitted record shows Samantha's authenticated confession (PX-4) that she had not read Stephenson before drafting and implied she had, while simultaneously assuring Peter the package would be complete by the March 11 handoff (PX-2). This false premise was integral to her timing assurance under the assignment terms (PX-1). Peter disclosed consequences","streamIndex":0}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"qwen/qwen3.5-plus-02-15","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1782756726877,"responseId":"gen-1782756727-9MhNrvS4NrtfYdIc6CZ7","responseModel":"qwen/qwen3.5-plus-20260216"}},"message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thin